{
  "doc_id": "4829",
  "text": "Supplemental oxygen in obstetrics is widely applied to routine practice because parturients carry a high risk of hypoxemia. Due to the physiological and anatomical changes occurring in pregnancy, maternal oxygen consumption increases, and the functional residual capacity decreases [CITATION_1] . A significant reduction in respiratory mechanics develops after spinal anesthesia for cesarean delivery [CITATION_2] . Nevertheless, there are a number of compensation mechanisms. Both maternal and fetal factors enhance the transfer of oxygen across the placenta and thereby prevent fetal hypoxemia.",
